rComments: Loved his class! He included lots of guest speakers + reflection activities (easy). He's v respectful and includes various perspectives + debunks myths about feminism; made the topic approachable. Exams: t/f, MCQ, & essay q's--you can prepare for them beforehand. VI is cool, the only issue is that there's no in-class time to work. Easy to get an A

Great class taught by a prof who's very passionate about the subject. It's an intro class so the information learnt is very basic but it was still fun. The only issue I had with this class/prof was that due dates weren't clearly stated. Assignments were simple but the class often felt disorganized.

Overall, I think that he was a good enough professor. He was passionate about the material and was encouraging and including with students. However, for assignments and instructions, he was often quite unclear. We had a project to do, and only a few days before did he release instructions even though this project called for quite a bit of effort.

the workload is acc not heavy at all, I barely give this class time outside the lectures watching them is enough to understand the material, and he provides everything you need to know. work is not hard and he's really nice and understanding :) fav class ngl

How is a man supposed to teach me about the struggle of women? I'm not sure there's a single thing more infuriating than being spoken at about the oppression of women from the perspective of a man? I can appreciate his educational background and will to be a feminist, but its strange the uni would let him teach this class.

I honestly can say he is the worst professor I've ever had. He teaches material that is outdated and uses examples that is not completely relevant anymore. It takes him forever to get through even one slide show. He is extremely opinionated and unless you share his opinion you're gonna feel "wrong" the entire semester.

The worst professor Ive ever had. Im a 4th year and took this class out of interest, but spare yourself and take another class. Doesnt answer student emails, rude, unprofessional, unclear expectations, and just an overall unpleasant person. Plus, a women, gender, and feminism class taught by a MAN doesnt really set itself up for success.

Prof Zaky had his heart in the right place. He was difficult at times to follow throughout the semester but tried to make his lectures engaging. He did struggle with zoom but I don't think that should be a reason not to take him. He let everyone pick from 3 choices for midterm & final and you did not need the lectures to do well.

I am a fourth year student who decided to take FEM1101 as it is a personal interest of mine. Prof Zaky is probably the worst prof Ive had in my four years at university. Zaky gives long, meandering, irrelevant lectures and makes himself unavailable to students. I spent the entire semester confused about what was expected of me. Avoid at all costs.

wasn't a great prof. He often forgot to record and had many difficulties with zoom which made it difficult, being a hybrid course. The textbook is necessary, you cant do the midterm or final without it. Didn't like how we only had 3 assignments that were all worth a huge percentage. you can tell he cared about his students but just wasn't for me.

This was a mandatory course for me, however if you are able to get a different professor I would highly suggest it. He listed the textbook as mandatory, but I didnt use it all term aside from the midterm and final (which you wouldnt have to depending on the assignment you chose). He gives very little feedback on assignments as well.
started his class today and I already want to call my mom and cry. just no. if you have the chance to drop this class do it.

Honestly, I would recommend him for this ARB course because he tries his best to make sure that students are graded fairly. One thing I would say is that he favours students who actually show up to class, so if you dont you definitely miss out on some of the bonus marks that he hands out and whatnot.

To be honest, I chose "clear grading criteria" tag cuz there is none for the opposite. This professor gives his broad rubrics by email so you have to scavenge for them when assignments are due and it was hard to get a clear answer on what he wanted. I was part of the CSL group and he only specified what he wanted after our project was already done

Really interesting course, many great Arab-Can guest lecturers, businesspeople, academics, artists/writers. Loved engaging with the students in the class and hearing everyone's opinions, super collaborative. Half synchronous and half asych, which was nice. Bi-weekly assignments, a group project, a project proposal, and final paper/project. Great!

IF YOU WANT A RUBRIC EVER, DON'T WASTE YOUR TIME. this professor insists that he wants feedback and that it means a lot to him, but he's lying. CLEARLY, people have been asking for rubrics on assignments for a while, considering his reviews. multiple people in this class asked for them and he just agreed but never did it. infuriating.
Awful!! Worst fem prof at the uni I swear. He doesnt use trigger warning and is so bad at lecturing. If you have the choice to take him dont.

He's a very sweet prof and is aggressively passionate about feminist studies lol. His FEM1100 course is very easy because it's just the basics but I really recommend it. It's an easy-going class, a one-group project, and the rest are self-explanatory. Lectures are optional, slides + textbooks should be more than enough! Totally recommend :D

Radamis is a great prof who made Feminist Theory relevant and connected to today. Don't miss a lecture, ask lots of questions, and do the extra credit. The only challenge was the assignments were frequent, but not scheduled. They felt chaotic in an otherwise great course.

Good guy but a terrible teacher. He is chaotic, gives last minute confusing instructions and have a pretty unclear grading criteria. 60% of the class grade is based on group projects which are completely useless and confusing!

Professor Zaky truly cares for his students and makes a great effort to build interesting courses with relevant content. Professor Zaky is definitely outspoken and I believe that this can be misinterpreted by some students as him not caring, or being too tough on the class, but after taking his course I believe he is passionate about teaching.

Argued with students if he didnt agree with them, even when they were talking about their lived experiences. Told students directly that they were lying to him. Instructions incredibly unclear and when that was brought to his attention he lashed out. Very forgetful and needed reminders to upload information he said he would upload months before.
Very lost person, he is a student and not sure why is he teaching. It was terrible experience overall. I did okay in terms of grade but I learned nothing in the class.

Probably the most accommodating professor during Covid! Prof. Zaky provided lots of assignments instead of exams and kept every lecture engaging. There were guest speakers almost every week which was SUPER interesting. Highly recommend!!!

How could a 10% assignment 250 words but a 2% weekly assignment 500 words? And he added a 900+ word essay for the final exam few weeks before the ending of the semester. A lot of "uh uh uh" while speaking so difficult to concentrate on what he's saying. He's a kind prof but doesn't give me a good experience. Better to choose another prof.

TAKEN DURING COVID-19*** He deducts marks based on criteria he didn't even mention to you. He is NOT clear when it comes to expectations. You have to email him almost daily in order to find out what he expects from you. Best way to deal with him is send him drafts of your projects. Terrible prof. Only upside is that there was no midterm. Easy A

Would not recommend. Copy paste readings on slides but with spelling/grammar errors that sometimes make them incomprehensible. Assignments timelines are unrealistic, no grading criteria until last minute, no rubric. Changes dates/assignments to last minute and expects quick turn around. Not receptive to feedback but claims to be "flexible".

Cons: Slides are text-heavy and basically from the readings. His grading criteria was not clear whatsoever, no rubrics. Rarely responds to emails or answers questions clearly. Was rude to students and argued with them. Final exam was a disaster (unfair & inconsistent). Pros: Guest lecturers were interesting.

This prof was very unorganized, rude, and did not provide clear expectations for any of his assignments or exams (he blamed his students for not understanding unclear content). The only good thing about his class were the guest lecturers. The course content COULD have been interesting, but his teaching style was all over the place and just bad.

Can be a little rude, he argued with students when he asked for their opinion, is not clear on what he wants for the assignments. Many spelling mistakes make it hard to understand. His exam was very unorganized. It was online which was cool but instructions are never clear. He forgets to post slides and goes very fast during class.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Participation matters', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: Would not recommend. Slidescopied from the readings except with several spelling/grammar errors that sometimes make them incomprehensible. Interesting assignments but he gives no grading criteria, no rubrics etc. but then marks super specifically and hard. Changes dates/assignments FREQUENTLY & doesn't post about it. Rude to students in class...
